---
import Base from '../../../layouts/Base.astro';
const title = 'Silent Engram';
const subtitle = 'A memory whose trace is intact and whose access is broken. Try the cue. Try the stimulation.';
---
<Base title={title} description={subtitle}>
  <article class="etude">
    <p class="essay-kicker">Etude · Memory</p>
    <h1>{title}</h1>
    <p class="essay-sub">{subtitle}</p>
    <div class="essay-meta">
      <a href="/essays/memory-was-never-about-storage/">← back to essay</a>
    </div>
    <hr />

    <p>Hold a memory in mind. A kitchen, summer 1996. Late afternoon light on a linoleum floor. Your grandmother's hands, dusted with flour, folding dough at the counter. The radio is on, low, in another room.</p>

    <p>The memory is stored. The trace is somewhere in the tissue. Whether you can <em>reach</em> it is a separate question.</p>

    <div class="askers">
      <button type="button" id="ask-cue" class="ask-btn">Try the natural cue</button>
      <button type="button" id="ask-stim" class="ask-btn ask-btn-graph">Direct stimulation</button>
    </div>

    <div id="answer" class="answer" aria-live="polite"></div>

    <hr />

    <p>The trace was never gone. The retrieval pathway was broken. Storage is fine; access is broken. Forgetting is loss of access, not loss of trace.</p>

    <p class="answer-detail">Background: Tonegawa and Josselyn's optogenetic engram work showed that memories invisible to natural cues can still be evoked by directly stimulating the engram cells that hold them — the trace persists even when the retrieval route fails. <a href="https://www.science.org/doi/10.1126/science.aaw4325">Memory engrams: Recalling the past and imagining the future</a>.</p>
  </article>
</Base>

<script is:inline>
  const cueAnswer = `<p class="answer-detail">...</p>
<p class="answer-detail">the cue passes. nothing surfaces. you go on with your day.</p>`;

  const stimAnswer = `<p class="answer-confident"><strong>The kitchen returns.</strong></p>
<p class="answer-detail">Flour on the counter, a fine pale dust along the edge of the wooden board. Her hands move without thinking — fold, press, quarter-turn, fold. The dough gives under her knuckles. Somewhere behind you, a screen door bangs once and settles. The radio is playing something with horns. You are seven, and the afternoon is enormous.</p>`;

  document.getElementById('ask-cue').addEventListener('click', () => {
    const el = document.getElementById('answer');
    el.innerHTML = '<p class="answer-detail">...</p>';
    el.dataset.mode = 'cue';
    setTimeout(() => {
      if (el.dataset.mode === 'cue') el.innerHTML = cueAnswer;
    }, 900);
  });
  document.getElementById('ask-stim').addEventListener('click', () => {
    const el = document.getElementById('answer');
    el.innerHTML = stimAnswer;
    el.dataset.mode = 'stim';
  });
</script>

<style>
  .etude { max-width: 38rem; margin: 0 auto; padding: 2rem 1.25rem 4rem; }
  .etude h1 { font-family: 'Georgia', serif; font-size: 2rem; margin: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem; }
  .essay-sub { font-style: italic; color: var(--muted); margin: 0 0 1rem; }
  .askers {
    display: flex;
    gap: 0.6rem;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
  }
  .ask-btn {
    font-family: inherit;
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    padding: 0.55rem 0.9rem;
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
    background: var(--bg);
    color: var(--ink);
    border-radius: 3px;
    cursor: pointer;
    transition: background 100ms;
  }
  .ask-btn:hover { background: rgba(138, 52, 32, 0.08); }
  .ask-btn-graph { border-style: solid; }
  .answer {
    margin: 1.25rem 0;
    min-height: 2rem;
  }
  .answer:not(:empty) {
    padding: 1rem 1.15rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--accent);
    background: rgba(138, 52, 32, 0.04);
    border-radius: 2px;
  }
  .answer-confident strong { color: var(--accent); }
  .answer-detail { color: var(--muted); font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.55; margin: 0.5rem 0; }
</style>
